external_knowledge:
- 'Average breath of the wind' refers to the average wind speed;
- 'Land of the free' refers to the USA;
- 'More than one data point' means `COUNT(location_id) > 1`.

- "High-elevation locations" refers to locations with an elevation greater than 100 meters;
- "Average weather conditions" include the average temperature and average humidity;
- "Over the past month" refers to the last 30 days.

- "Fresh breeze" is a term used in weather forecasting, indicating a wind speed of 17-21 knots (31-39 km/h);
- "White horses" refer to the white foam or spray that appears on the crests of waves during strong winds;
- "Moderate waves taking a more pronounced long form" describes the sea conditions where waves are not just choppy but have a longer, more defined shape.

- 'Highest average wind speeds' refers to the locations with the greatest average wind speeds in February;
- 'Previous locations' refers to the locations that had the next highest average wind speeds in the same month;
- 'Active users' are those whose status is 'active' and who have logged in within the last 30 days;
- 'Reliable weather data' is defined as data with a 'high' reliability rating.

- The temperature difference is calculated as the average temperature of a location minus the average temperature of the country where the location is situated;
- The location with the highest positive temperature difference is considered to stand out the most;
- The query assumes that the location name contains the country name as a substring.

- A user is associated with a specific location in the database;
- The most recent weather data is determined by the latest date and time for each location;
- Wind speed is measured in km/h, temperature in degrees Celsius, and humidity in percentage.

- Wind speed is typically measured in kilometers per hour (km/h);
- The presence of null values in latitude, longitude, and temperature can affect the ranking and thus the final results;
- The query ranks locations and weather data to prioritize records with complete information.

- Wind speed is measured in kilometers per hour (km/h);
- Temperature is measured in degrees Celsius (°C);
- Julian day is a continuous count of days since the beginning of the Julian period and is used to represent dates and times in a single numerical value.

- The highest wind speed is determined by ranking the wind speeds in descending order within each location;
- The average wind speed is calculated by averaging the wind speeds for each location;
- The wind speed values are in km/h.

- "Strong winds" are defined as wind speeds greater than 20 km/h;
- "Recently" refers to the most recent data collection date for each location;
- "Winds roaring like a lion" is a metaphor for strong, powerful winds.

- Ideal wind speed: 10 km/h;
- Ideal temperature: 20°C;
- Ideal humidity: 60%;
- "Out of tune with the ideal climate" means the weather conditions deviate significantly from the ideal values.
